social_posts.post_text: always evolving 🌹

I used to post more of myself exterior wise, then I had this grand shift and pull to show more of my inner being. Now when I look at my page, I see it as less of a mental mess, and more of an intentional showing of who I authentically am. I’ve outgrown past selves. The blossoming is less vomity and more gradual. I’m proud to see myself show up in the way my future self imagined. It’s effing beautiful and freeing letting go of these false narratives and seeking validations that no longer serve you.🌹 

Needless to say, it’s been awhile since I’ve posted a ‘self/me’🤳🏼 I was feeling my makeup I did this day, with the sunshine, no filter, naturally glowing.✨
Something to reflect on 💭🙏🏽

The moment I met my biological Aunt Lena in Russia, 2021. One of the first things she said was “You look like your Mama”…. in this moment I didn’t know how to process it, I’ve had little to no memory of my Mama or what happened to her, it’s always been memories of my Papa. 

On this Mother’s Day, I not only think of my adoptive Mom, but my Birth Mama. Mama Женя. I don’t have a photo to hold, I don’t have her connection, but I have only a few things that I do know and can feel on: She was short just like me, She had a warm genuine smile, She was beautiful inside and out, and She named me Valentina (meaning strong and brave) after her Mother. In this video, I feel very one with her presence, I see her light in me. 

I understand a lot of us adoptees have different emotions and feelings on this day and any other, about their Birth parents. But for me, I only have love for Her. I pray for the day I find more answers about her and I can hold a picture. I can stare at her beauty. I can see myself in her. Until then, I can feel on these other wonderful things about her.

I love you Mama, wherever you are, whatever happened, living or passed. I long for a big deep hug heart to heart with you. I long to hold you and to be held. You are more instilled on my soul as I grow to be older. You are my butterfly. 🦋🥲

I’ve been doing this ‘work’ for awhile now, but it definitely is starting to hit me just how much I’ve changed and grown to become a totally different version and my new self. It all started with being tired of my own shit, being aware, taking responsibility, action, and consciously choosing. We may not always see the whole staircase but those individual steps lead us there, and the views are amazing as I climb to my (highest self). SHE is arriving and thriving internally, and that’s what matters the most. Keep going, keep growing, keep glowing!✨

We often feel imposter syndrome as opportunities and blessings arrive…Why? Because we are still learning to accept and settle in to our own abundance, worth, and deservingness. Instead of questioning ourselves if we’re ready and allowing past scarcity beliefs and mindsets to creep in, let’s reshift our thinking and say:

I deserve this. I am worthy. I am ready. This is meant for me. I trust myself. I trust God and the Universe. I am grateful. I am showing up. I am confident.

It’s interesting how our personal reality creates our personality. Not feeling protected or safe, my little Dasha self didn’t have much of a choice to take on a matured role for myself. To act and be an older person. My inner child never got the true chance to just be and play. This role I’d carry out in to guiding and nurturing other children in the orphanages. I’d speak up for myself and for others. This role has made me who I am today. What a beautiful realization, while a somewhat sad reality at times. But I think the most magical part is seeing how I’d turn our traumas in to creative adventures (make friends with birch trees, eat leaves for ‘nutrition’), my little heart was still at play🩵

#RussianAmericanAdoptee #RussianAdoptee #AdopteeJourney #AdopteeStory #AdopteeVoice

I long to go back and take a deep dive of connection with my family and my roots, one day soon, for an extended time🙏🏽🦋

International adoptees get critiqued, judged, and assumed based off how Americanized we/they are, vs where we actually come from. It needs to stop. Invalidating any culture of them looking or sounding or being from there is such a micro aggression. 

1) the narrow mindedness of not ‘looking’ a culture, when really they can’t see it only because we don’t sound or speak that language.

2) constantly proving our genetics to others when they have no idea of the triggers and trauma it brings up for us with these ‘basic’ questions that they’ll just shrug off the answer to

3) other’s instill an opinion of us that’s so deeply unnecessary 

4) let’s do better, and simply hear/acknowledge, or better yet become more curious about each other 🙏🏽

“Benji and Buster” are two bonded brother pups that I found free roaming the streets one night. After I safely took them in, we went to the vet to check their microchips. I met with their owners, who unfortunately relinquished them. They are now in my care, (a fun handful!🤪) as well as cared for and sponsored by @aceofheartsdogrescue organization, until they find their furever home.🩵

Today was their first adoption event/meet and greet! They did so great and got all the love and cuddles. I stayed with them and helped along with the event. These other sweet souls were also there and available for adoption. If you feel called to any of them, please reach out or share this post/help spread the word for them, or even help donate (link in my bio). Please support adopting and not shopping! There are so many rescued boys and girls that need our help first! 🐶🙏🏽

#dogrescue #rescuedog #rescuepup #rescueorganization #rescue #adoptdontshop

As a China rescue, saved from the dog meat trades, I only imagine what my LuLu and so many other innocent street dogs have gone through. Fighting to survive, find safety, dumpster dive, and who knows what they even ate or what else they experienced… when I see my LuLu happy and grounding herself, I know that she is at peace. We are one soul that both came from similar traumas, her happiness fulfills me.

When I found them wandering the streets (all the way back in September now), I had no idea what sort of journey God was preparing us to go on. Without a second thought, I picked them up in one arm and had my electric scooter in the other, and brought them safely inside my home. I washed them up and expected to get them back to their worried, loving family the next day. Unfortunately that wasn’t the case when they were relinquished over. My adoptee heart (knowing abandonment and relinquishment well) was not only broken for them, but in shock. I didn’t know how I could take on 2 rescue pups at the time, but I knew I was given this specific mission. 

Getting 2 pups to be adopted together can sometimes take time, so we are excited about them being seen more and potential families being interested in them. I know the time is quickly approaching now as they manifest their furever home. It’s always bittersweet but so worth it in all of the emotions from the day I picked them up in one arm. Please if you can ever help a dog in need, do. Please seek help if you can’t care for an animal. Please adopt and don’t shop. There are so many animals already in need of a home like these two. Rescue is the best breed. 🤍🐶
